<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-142-114 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 969 954</DOCID><JOURNAL>Networking Management  June 1991 v9 n7 p92(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>A market in the making: wireless PBXs. (Commentary) (column)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Gantz, John.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Wireless local area networks are now a reality and wireless PBXand key telephone systems (KTS) are coming fast.andP;  Wirelesspremises are a promising market because vendors are looking forsomething to replace flat or negative PBX and KTS sales, personalcommunications networks are expected and they will mean the samemobile phone is used in the office and on the road, and practicalexperience will help lower barriers to market launch.andP;  It isbecoming clear that the payoff in wireless PBX and KTS will be inlower phone bills because of increased competition, not in reducedcabling costs.andP;  A 1990 survey of the PBX market shows thatrespondents think the most valuable features will be easypersonnel relocation, reduced labor costs, no inside wiring,portability, and personal computer/LAN connectivity.andP;  A clearmarket demand for wireless PBX and KTS is not yet present, but itis coming.andP;  Ultimately, the new applications that are madepossible by wireless PBX and KTS are what will make those systemsthe most valuable.andP;  The technical challenges presented byallocating spectrum and designing an in-building radio networkwill be overcome.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     PBXTrendsLocal Area NetworksFuture of ComputingWireless NetworksTelephone SystemsMarket AnalysisMarket EntryCritiqueCar PhonesKey/Hybrid Telephone Systems.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>